#compdef vimv
# =============================================================================
# vimv — a command-line utility for batch-renaming files using a text editor.
#        Created by Darren Mulholland (dmulholl), vimv opens the list of
#        files in your $EDITOR (one filename per line), waits for you to
#        edit the names + save + close, then renames the files to match
#        your edits.  Supports cycle-renaming (A→B, B→C, C→A all in one
#        operation), directory creation along renamed paths, and trash-
#        based deletion via `#`-prefix.
#
# Author:  Darren Mulholland (dmulholl)
# Source:  https://github.com/dmulholl/vimv
# CLI:     src/main.rs (uses dmulholl/arguably)
# Library: dmulholl/arguably
#          ("A minimalist argument-parsing library for Rust")
# License: Unlicense
# Status:  Stable — 94+ stars, available via `cargo install vimv`.
#          Adopted as the canonical "batch rename via $EDITOR" tool
#          across multiple Linux distros and macOS via Homebrew.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — RUST CROSSES TO 27 LIBRARIES
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents the
# 27TH Rust CLI library variant.  Rust climbs from 26 to 27 documented
# libraries (arguably via vimv).  New leaderboard: Rust=27 (SOLO LEAD),
# Go=26, TypeScript-Node=26.  Taxonomy now spans 217 cross-language CLI
# library variants across 52 documented languages.
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS arguably AND WHY IS IT A DISTINCT 27TH RUST CLI LIBRARY VARIANT?
#
# arguably (https://github.com/dmulholl/arguably, 19+ stars) is Darren
# Mulholland's command-line argument parsing library for Rust.  Darren is
# the author of a family of similar minimal CLI libraries across multiple
# languages: arguably (Rust, THIS), args (Go), Janus (Python — once popular
# pre-Click), Janus-Cpp (C++), and Pylon-Cpp.  All of them follow the same
# design template: minimal builder API + space-separated name aliases +
# string-keyed accessor lookups.  arguably is the ONLY Rust member of this
# family.
#
# arguably's defining characteristics distinguishing it from other Rust
# CLI libraries:
#
#   1. SPACE-SEPARATED NAME ALIASES — flag/option declarations take a
#      space-separated string with both long and short names together:
#         parser.flag("force f")            // --force AND -f
#         parser.flag("quiet q")             // --quiet AND -q
#         parser.option("editor e", "")      // --editor AND -e
#      This is the FIRST documented Rust CLI library where MULTIPLE
#      ALIASES ARE DECLARED IN A SINGLE STRING with whitespace as the
#      separator.  Compare clap's `.short('f').long("force")`, structopt's
#      `#[structopt(short, long)]`, getargs' `Opt::Short('f') | Opt::Long
#      ("force")`, lapp's `-f, --force` in USAGE text.  arguably's
#      whitespace-separated alias list is more compact than any of these.
#
#   2. STRING-KEYED ACCESSOR LOOKUP — after parsing, results are queried
#      by string name:
#         parser.found("force")          // bool: was the flag set?
#         parser.value("editor")          // string: extracted value
#         parser.args                     // Vec<String>: positionals
#      No struct-tag, no derive, no type inference.  This is the SIMPLEST
#      possible result API but trades static type safety for runtime
#      string keys.  Closest match: stdlib HashMap<String, Value>.
#
#   3. HELPTEXT-AS-DISPLAY (NOT AS SPEC) — `parser.helptext(STR)` sets the
#      help text that is printed on `-h`/`--help`.  Unlike lapp (R464)
#      where the helptext IS parsed into the spec, or docopt where the
#      helptext IS the spec, arguably's helptext is DISPLAY-ONLY.  The
#      actual flag declarations come from `.flag()`/`.option()` calls.
#      This separation lets the helptext be ANY shape — multi-paragraph,
#      with examples, with sections — without needing to fit into a
#      machine-parseable format.
#
#   4. MINIMAL FLUENT BUILDER — only 4 main methods: `.helptext(STR)`,
#      `.version(STR)`, `.flag(NAMES)`, `.option(NAMES, DEFAULT)`.  No
#      typed value methods (`int_opt1` like lapp), no positional
#      declarations (positionals are auto-collected into `parser.args`),
#      no subcommand support (subcommands handled at the caller level
#      via dispatch on `parser.args[0]`).  This is the MINIMAL viable
#      CLI library API for Rust.
#
#   5. CROSS-LANGUAGE DESIGN HERITAGE — arguably's API is a DIRECT PORT
#      of Darren Mulholland's earlier Janus (Python) and Args (Go)
#      libraries.  The same `parser.found("name")` / `parser.value("name")`
#      pattern appears across all three.  This makes arguably the FIRST
#      documented Rust CLI library that is part of a CROSS-LANGUAGE
#      FAMILY of CLI libraries by the same author.  Compare lapp (R464,
#      also a Lua-to-Rust port by Steve Donovan) which is a similar
#      cross-language transplant — but lapp's design transferred WHOLESALE
#      while arguably is independently authored per language with shared
#      conventions but distinct implementations.
#
#   6. `parser.parse() -> Result<(), Error>` ERROR-AS-VALUE PROTOCOL —
#      parse failures return a `Error` value with `.exit()` method that
#      prints to stderr and calls process::exit().  This is similar to
#      anyhow but argument-parsing-specific; errors carry the usage
#      context.
#
# THE arguably API SURFACE (verbatim from vimv usage)
#
#   use arguably::ArgParser;
#
#   let mut parser = ArgParser::new()
#       .helptext(HELPTEXT)                       // set --help text
#       .version(env!("CARGO_PKG_VERSION"))       // set --version output
#       .flag("force f")                          // bool flag, both forms
#       .flag("quiet q")
#       .flag("stdin s")
#       .option("editor e", "");                  // value flag, both forms,
#                                                 // default empty string
#
#   if let Err(err) = parser.parse() {
#       err.exit();
#   }
#
#   // Result access:
#   parser.found("force")        // → bool
#   parser.value("editor")        // → String
#   parser.args                   // → Vec<String> (positionals)
#
# CONTRAST WITH OTHER MINIMAL RUST CLI LIBRARIES DOCUMENTED IN THE CORPUS
#
#   * pico-args (R347)           — pull-based: "ask for what you need"
#   * lexopt (R407)              — iterator-based: "yield each arg"
#   * gumdrop (R410)             — older derive-based
#   * lapp (R464)                — usage-text-as-spec
#   * onlyargs (R445)            — minimal no-derive
#   * getargs (R471)             — zero-cost iterator
#   * noargs (R474)              — imperative "consuming take"
#   * arguably (THIS)            — minimal builder, space-separated aliases,
#                                  string-keyed accessor
#
# arguably is the MOST CHARACTER-EFFICIENT of these for declaring a CLI
# with multiple short/long aliases.  A 4-flag binary in arguably is ~5
# lines; the same in clap-derive is ~25 lines; in lexopt/getargs it's
# ~30 lines of imperative match.  arguably trades type-safety for
# brevity.
#
# REAL-WORLD arguably USERS:
#
#   * dmulholl/vimv — batch-rename via $EDITOR (THIS, 94*)
#   * dmulholl/intspector — integer conversion utility (4*)
#   * dmulholl/hexbomb — stylish hexdump (6*)
#   * kbogtob/runiq — alternative uniq tool
#   * twilio-labs/receptionist-bot-rs — Twilio receptionist bot (production)
#   * Many of Darren Mulholland's other Rust utilities
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# VIMV'S CLI SURFACE (verbatim from src/main.rs HELPTEXT)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# USAGE:
#   vimv [files]
#
# WORKFLOW:
#   1. Run `vimv [list of files]` (or `vimv` alone in a directory)
#   2. vimv opens the file list in $EDITOR with one path per line
#   3. Edit names + save + exit
#   4. vimv applies the diffs as renames
#
# Special features:
#   * CYCLE RENAMING — vimv detects A→B, B→C, C→A cycles and renames
#     atomically without temp-file dance.
#   * DELETION VIA `#`-PREFIX — prefix any line with `#` to send the
#     file/directory to system trash (uses `trash` crate; respects
#     XDG_DATA_HOME on Linux, ~/.Trash on macOS, Recycle Bin on Win).
#   * AUTO-LISTING — invoking `vimv` with no args opens the current
#     directory's contents in $EDITOR.
#   * DIRECTORY CREATION — if a renamed path contains new directories,
#     vimv creates them.
#
# Arguments:
#   [files]                List of files to rename (optional; defaults
#                          to current directory contents if absent and
#                          --stdin not set)
#
# Options:
#   -e, --editor <name>    Specify the editor to use (overrides $EDITOR)
#
# Flags:
#   -f, --force            Allow overwriting existing files
#                          (existing DIRECTORIES are still never overwritten)
#   -h, --help             Print help text and exit
#   -q, --quiet            Quiet mode — only report errors
#   -s, --stdin            Read the list of input files from stdin
#   -v, --version          Print version number and exit
#
# =============================================================================

_vimv() {
    local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s \
        '(-e --editor)'{-e,--editor}'[specify editor (overrides $EDITOR)]:editor:_command_names -e' \
        '(-f --force)'{-f,--force}'[allow overwriting existing files]' \
        '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
        '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[quiet mode — only report errors]' \
        '(-s --stdin)'{-s,--stdin}'[read input file list from stdin]' \
        '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[print version and exit]' \
        '*:file to rename:_files' \
        && ret=0

    return ret
}

_vimv "$@"
